NEW YORK, 2013

One of my favorite spots in Manhattan to people watch, maybe second to Washington Square Park is the lovely Bethesda Fountain in Central Park, well except when there’s a snow storm like there was on March 1, 2015 this year. I was feeling OK on that Sunday and decided to wander around the park despite the snow and make my way over to Bethesda Terrace and the Fountain. So with my trusty weather-sealed Olympus E-5, using weather-sealed Olympus Zuiko Digital 12-60mm F2.8-4.0 lens, through the park I ventured towards my goal, the snowfall steadily increasing. In my earlier postings of Central Park, I’ve written about the Greensward plan submitted entry #33 turned in by Frederick Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux which won , and the entry included in the original submission a two level terrace and central fountain. Vaux referred to the fountain as “the centre of the centre.” The beautiful statue at its center the ‘Angels of the Waters’ was designed by sculptor Emma Stebbins, who was the first woman to who received a public art commission from the city of New York and was the only major sculpture commissioned for Central Park during its original design and construction. The Angel of the Waters refers to the Gospel of John and the Pool of Bethesda which had healing powers when blessed by an angel. In my photostream, I have a closer shot of the 26 foot beautiful fountain see this link flic.kr/p/e6ZGtN Back to March 1st, I made my way to the Bethesda Terrace and the Bethesda Fountain. Unlike other times in the year, there were very few around the fountain. The special eyepiece on the E-5 got frozen and fogged , so I had to remove it. I shot this image on manual exposure, dug a spot for the Slik tripod, processed the RAW file in Adobe Lightroom. Here’s a link to another image on my photostream on how it looks in the summer flic.kr/p/eEcdUE www.centralparknyc.org/things-to-see-and-do/attractions/b...

description._content: The Steven A. Schwarzman Building of the New York Public Library is located where Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street intersect. This beautiful example of Beaux-Arts style was opened in 1911 as the main branch of the New York Public Library, consolidating several libraries on the eastern portion of what was the Croton Reservoir which was outdated and no longer in service. There are actually some remnants from the reservoir visible in areas of the current library. The firm of Carrère and Hastings was hired to design the impressive building that would at the time of its completion, the largest marble structure in the USA, with Vermont Marble 3 feet thick for its walls. The majestic entranceway on Fifth Avenue is impressive as captured here in this image, taken in August 2014. Being a part of the last leg of the baby boomers, being in college in the 1980’s, I will probably always relate this wonderful edifice with the movie Ghostbusters which features this very library in its opening scenes with Doctors Egon Spengler, Peter Venkman and Ray Stanz have their encounter with a paranormal being in the book stacks. The building with the lit spire that seems to protrude from its roof is the Bank of America Tower that is a block down on 42nd and Sixth Avenue. Taken with Olympus E-5 with Olympus Zuiko Digital 14-42mm F3.5-5.6 lens, using the Olympus E-5 built-in creative filter processed in Adobe Lightroom. www.nypl.org/about/locations/schwarzman/visitor-guide

Dating back to 1936, the Neon 147 foot long & 50 foot high Pepsi -Cola sign/billboard that since 2009 sits on the waterfront at Gantry Plaza State Park once sat upon the roof of Pepsi-Cola’s bottling plant located right behind where the sign is today. Pepsi’s origins actually go back to 1898, in New Bern, North Carolina. New York City became the company headquarters after Pepsi-Cola’s second bankruptcy in 1931; the National Pepsi-Cola Company was acquired by the Loft Candy Company and eventually Loft’s and Pepsi-Cola president Charles G. Guth moved Pepsi-Cola operations to Long Island City in 1936. The production facility was the largest bottling facility in the United States at the time, it’s location on the East River facilitating ships delivering sugar cane from Havana and other Pepsi ingredients. The remarkable Neon Pepsi-Cola sign adorned the roof of that building, joining other Neon signs that lined the East River representing the cradle of manufacturing that Long Island City was during that era. The sign was built by Artkraft Strauss Sign Corporation with an Art Deco cursive script and the same company refurbished the sign in 1994. The Pepsi bottling facility at Long Island City shut down in 1998. The property was offered for sale with one stipulation. The Pepsi-Cola Company, the New York/Queens community and the New York City Landmark commission came to an agreement that the historically important sign had to be preserved. Taken with an Olympus E-5 with a 12-60mm F/2.8-4.0 Olympus Zuiko Digital Lens, tone mapped using Photomatix, cleaned up in Adobe Lightroom. www.pepsibrattleboro.com/historyofPepsi

Every year on the first Sunday in May, 40 miles of street, highway and bridges are made free of cars in all five boroughs, Manhattan, Bronx, Queens, Brooklyn and Staten Island, so that 32,000 bicyclist can ride through the city in the TD Five Boro Bike Tour. I was able to ride this past Sunday (with some degree of difficulty because the extra body weight and health issues) in this wonderful event, my fourth time overall, the third time in the last four years. It is a wonderful event put together by the organization Bike New York which uses the proceeds from this event, the largest charitable bike ride, to fund the free bike education program which in 2014 educated over 16,000 children and adults with bicycle skills. Riders come from all over the United States and even from many different countries to participate, all skill levels, young and old. Along the way the riders are cheered by bystanders and entertained by various musicians. This image is of the starting line in lower Manhattan in the shadows of the World Trade Center, a sea of bicyclists as far as the eye could see eager to get rolling in the early morning hours. This was captured on an Olympus TG-850, processed with Photomatix, cleaned up in Adobe Photoshop Lightroom. www.bike.nyc/events/td-five-boro-bike-tour/

American sculptor Tom Fruin designed this colorful stained glass house for the 2014 DUMBO Arts Festival in Brooklyn and it is quite a spectacle to look at. Titled Kolonihavehus (Danish for ‘Garden House’), this stained glass art installation proved to be the most popular piece and was voted the 2014 DUMBO Arts Festival Audience Favorite with nearly double the votes of its nearest competitor! You can still see Fruin's Kolonihavehus in Brooklyn Bridge Park. The installation will be on view through June 2015. Don't miss it! Twitter Instagram

Times Square, New York, NY. Times Square in New York City is the home of famed Broadway shows, the New York Times, and is the official capital of the entertainment industry. It is the most visited place in the world, the most lit up, and the home of the largest billboards in the world. No wonder then that it is also the busiest pedestrian crossing in the world. Simply put, it is the “cross roads of the world and the center of the universe.” There are people, all sorts of them, some super heroes, a few Broadway actors, lots of tourists, and many an Elvis. The whole gamut of colors with full intensity is seen here! There are sounds everywhere, from music to sirens, to protesters drums, to loud and continuous honking. It is loud, livid, vivid and obnoxious! In Times Square, no lens is wide enough, no sensor has the all the tonal range and I am simply inadequate to capture this chaos. Here is my best attempt to 'portray’ Times Square! Please follow me on My Website | Facebook | Google+ | tumblr |

What Caused the Irish Potato Famine? The Memorial represents a rural Irish landscape with an abandoned stone cottage, stone walls, fallow potato fields and the flora on the north Connacht wetlands. It is both a metaphor for the Great Irish Famine and a reminder that hunger today is often the result of lack of access to land. The Irish Hunger Memorial, designed by artist Brian Tolle, contains stones from each of Ireland’s 32 counties.

El Flushing Meadows–Corona Park, usualmente llamado Flushing Meadow Park o Flushing Meadows Park, está ubicado al norte de Queens, Ciudad de Nueva York, Estados Unidos, en la intersección de la Long Island Expressway y la Grand Central Parkway. Es el segundo parque público más grande de la ciudad de Nueva York (luego del Central Park en Manhatan), fue creado para alojar la Feria Mundial de Nueva York 1939/1940 y en él tuvo lugar la Feria mundial Nueva York 1964. El parque es mantenido y operado por el Departamento de Parques y Recreación de la Ciudad de Nueva York. El parque se encuentra situado al borde este del área comprendida por la Cuarta Junta Comunal de Queens.
----------------
Flushing Meadows–Corona Park, often referred to as Flushing Meadows Park, or simply Flushing Meadows, is a public park in New York City. Located in the borough of Queens, it is between I-678 (Van Wyck Expressway) and the Grand Central Parkway, and stretches from Flushing Bay, at the southern edge of LaGuardia Airport, to Union Turnpike. It contains the USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center, the current venue for the U.S. Open tennis tournament; Citi Field, the home of the New York Mets baseball team; the New York Hall of Science, the Queens Museum of Art, the Queens Theatre in the Park, the Queens Wildlife Center, and the New York State Pavilion. It formerly contained Shea Stadium, demolished in 2009

West 42nd Street 26/04/2015 20h13 Photo taken about 30 minutes after sunset in the West 42nd Street opposite Bryant Park and just before the crossroad with the Avenue of the Americas (6th Avenue). 42nd Street 42nd Street is a major crosstown street in the New York City borough of Manhattan, known for its theaters, especially near the intersection with Broadway at Times Square. It is also the name of the region of the theater district (and, at times, the red-light district) near that intersection. The street has held a special place in New Yorkers' imaginations since at least the turn of the 20th century, and is the site of some of New York's best known buildings, including (east to west) the United Nations, Chrysler Building, Grand Central Terminal, Times Square and the Port Authority Bus Terminal. The corner of 42nd Street and Broadway, at the southeast corner of Times Square, was the eastern terminus of the Lincoln Highway, the first road across the United States, which begins on 42nd Street and continues to San Francisco, California and which was conceived and mapped in 1913. The New Whitney Museum Building, pretty much completed on the outside, its interior feverishly being worked on for the grand opening on May 1 2015, to be followed by free admission to museum on Saturday May 2 with a block party there in the Meat Packing district and the Highline Park. The beautiful creation of architect Renzo Piano situated between the southernmost part of the Highline Park and the Hudson River in nearly complete in this image taken in early April 2015. The beautiful asymmetrical structure features 50,000 square feet of indoor galleries and 13,000 square feet of outdoor exhibition space that will face the Highline Park. The museum’s current uptown address is currently closed as the move and preparations for the grand opening continue. That location will be used by the Metropolitan Museum of Art going forward for the time being. This new location brings the museum closer to where the original museum that was founded by Gertrude Whitney in 1930 in Greenwich Village which is really next door. I had posted a picture on my photostream of the museum in progress a few years back see this link[ flic.kr/p/ebsN7o ]. Taken handheld with Olympus E-5, manual using a 12-60mm F/2.8-4.0 Olympus Zuiko Digital Lens, raw file processed using Adobe Lightroom. whitney.org/
